Methylsilane and silanes The six silanes in Table 4 were parameterized by adjusting only the hydrogen atoms attached to silicon. For CM1A, these hydrogens were made less negative, while for CM1P, they were made more negative, as illustrated in Fig. 9. By virtue of the charge balance requirement, the charge on silicon is brought into general accord with the ab initio ChelpG results. CM1 dipole moments are slightly better than those from the Mulliken charges or from the wave function.
Methanethiol and sulfur compounds Sulfur is made more negative by the present CM1 mappings, and the hydrogens attached to sulfur are made more positive by the mechanism of local charge balance, as illustrated in Fig. 10. The dipole moments of nine sulfur compounds are improved by nearly an order of magnitude with CM1A and CM1P.
